.TH Gcost 2G G-language
.SH NAME
 Gcost \- Generate a cumulative cost map
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IP \fBGcost\fR
\fInewmap oldmap E,N [E,N] ...\fR
.IP \fBGcost\fR
\fInewmap oldmap\fR
.IP \fBGcost\fR
output=\fInewmap\fR input=\fIoldmap\fR coor=\fIE,N\fR [coor=\fIE,N\fR] ...
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I Gcost
evaluates an existing cost surface with respect to
starting locations in grid coordinates.  Each cell of the cost
surface will contain a value
which represents the cost of traversing that grid cell.  The
output result will contain the lowest total cost of traversing
the space between any of the starting locations and
each of the grid cells in the current window.
(Diagonal costs are multiplied by a factor that depends on the dimensions
of the grid cell.)
Consider the following example:

.NF
Input:                            Output:
   COST SURFACE                      CUMULATIVE COST SURFACE
 . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
 . 2 . 2 . 1 . 1 . 5 . 5 . 5 .     . 22. 20. 18. 17. 19. 17. 16.
 . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
 . 2 . 2 . 8 . 8 . 5 . 2 . 1 .     . 22. 21. 26. 22. 16. 12. 11.
 . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
 . 7 . 1 . 1 . 8 . 2 . 2 . 2 .     . 26. 19. 18. 19. 11. 10. 11.
 . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
 . 8 . 7 . 8 . 8 . 7 . 5 . 5 .     . 28. 20. 18. 17. 13. 8 . 10.
 . . . . . . . . . . _____ . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
 . 8 . 8 . 1 . 1 . 5 | 3 | 9 .     . 22. 18. 10. 9 . 8 . 0 . 12.
 . . . . . . . . . . |___| . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
 . 8 . 1 . 1 . 2 . 5 . 3 . 9 .     . 19. 11. 10. 11. 10. 6 . 16.
 . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
.FI

The user-provided starting location in the above example is
the boxed 3 in the left-hand map.   The costs in the output
represent the total cost of moving from each box to one or more
(in this case there is only one) starting location(s).  This
output map can be viewed as an elevation model where the
starting location(s) is/are the lowest point(s).  The
.I Gdrain
program can now be used to trace the least-cost path in this
model between any given grid cell and the
.I Gcost
starting
location(s).  The two programs, when used together, generate
least-cost paths or corridors between any two locations.
.SH OPTIONS
.I Gcost
can be run with two different methods of identifying the
starting point(s).  One or more points can be provided on
the command line.  In lieu of command line coordinates, a map of
starting point (e.g., start_pt_map)
may already exist.
Primarily filled with zeros, this map contains non-zero values
at the starting grid cell(s).  To submit the \fIstart_pt_map\fR, set
output=\fIstart_pt_map\fR.  Beware: doing this will overwrite
\fIstart_pt_map \fR with the results of the calculations.
If start_pt_map does exist and
points are also given on the command line, the start_pt_map is
ignored and the coordinates are used instead.  The input options are as follows:
.IP "input=\fImapname\fR"
Name of cell map containing grid cell cost information.
.IP "output=\fImapname\fR"
Name of cell map to contain results.  Also can be used as the map of
the input starting points.  If so used, the input starting point map
will be overwritten by the output.
.IP "coor=\fIE,N\fR"
These are the map E and N grid coordinates of a starting
point.  This option can be repeated for as many points
as desired.
.SH BUGS
If you submit the starting point map on the command line by typing:
.br
\fBoutput=start_pt_map\fR
.br
the starting point map will be overwritten by the calculated output.  It
is wise to copy (use the GRASS \fIcopy\fR tool) the starting
points map to another name before submission in 
.I Gcost;
otherwise
it will disappear.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
\fIcopy[1], Gdrain[2G]\fR
.SH AUTHOR
Antony Awaida, Intelligent Engineering Systems Laboratory, M.I.T.
